Tree-Structured Models

We can see from above that Decision trees are tree-structured models that find application in both classification and regression tasks.

Decision Tree Jargon

  • The very top of our tree is called our root node and it splits our data based upon categorical or numeric thresholds
  • We filter down into our internal nodes which have arrows pointing towards and away which split our data into subsets
  • Leaves are our final and last decision about that data and what class they fall into

How Do We Decide Which Variable To Use for Our Nodes?

  1. If we consider the decision tree above we can see that various internal nodes do not perfectly seperate our classes and are thus impure nodes. Because none of our leave nodes are 100% True or False they are all considered impure.
  1. Therefore, we want to find which variables split our training data into the purest subsets at each node.
  1. What formula will we use to determine node purity? Which Seperation is the Best? We need a way to measure and compare impurity

Impurity Measures

There are couple of impurity measures, but for this notebook we will focus on:

  1. Entropy
  1. Gini Impurity (Sklearn Default setting)

Entropy

Measures the randomness in the infromation being processed or we can say it is the measurement of the impurity or randomness in the data points. We can also think of entropy as the amount of information needed to accurately describe some sample. The higher the entropy, the harder it is to draw any conclusions from that information.

Low

$$ \begin{bmatrix} \\ A & A & A & A \\ \ \end{bmatrix}$$

Medium

$$ \begin{bmatrix} \\ A & A & A & B \\ \ \end{bmatrix}$$

High

$$ \begin{bmatrix} \\ A & A & B & B \\ \ \end{bmatrix}$$

If we pick a 4 random letter out of each set, what is the probability that we get the same letters in their original order?

$$\begin{array}{c|c} & P(A) & P(B) & P(Same) & -log(P(Same)) & Entropy \\ \hline AAAA & 1 & 0 & 1 \times 1 \times 1 \times 1 = 1 & 0 + 0 + 0 + 0 & 0 \\ \hline AAAB & 0.75 & 0.25 & 0.75 \times 0.75 \times 0.75 \times 0.25 = 0.105 & 0.415 + 0.415 + 0.415 + 2 & 0.81\\ \hline AABB & 0.5 & 0.5 & 0.5 \times 0.5 \times 0.5 \times 0.5 = 0.0625 & 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 & 1\\ \end{array}$$

Entropy Formula

$$Entropy = - \sum_{i=1}^{n}p_ilog\hat{p_i}$$
$$AAAA = -\frac{4}{4}log_2(\frac{4}{4})-\frac{0}{4}log_2(\frac{0}{4}) = 0$$$$$$


$$AAAB = -\frac{3}{4}log_2(\frac{3}{4})-\frac{1}{4}log_2(\frac{1}{4}) = 0.81$$ $$$$
$$AABB = -\frac{2}{4}log_2(\frac{2}{4})-\frac{2}{4}log_2(\frac{2}{4}) = 1$$

Gini Impurity

Gini index is measure of inequality in the nodes. It calculates the amount of probability of a specific feature that is classified incorrectly when selected randomly. If all the elements are linked with a single class then it can be called pure. It has value between 0 and 1. Gini index of value 0 means sample are perfectly homogeneous and all element are similar.

Gini Formula

$$Gini = 1 - \sum_{k=1}^{n}(p_{i,k})^{2}$$$$$$

$p_i,k$ is the ratio of class k instances among the training instances in the $i^{th}$ node.

Classification

The CART Training Algorithm

Scikit-Learn uses the Classification And Regression Tree (CART) algorithm to train Decision Trees

This algorithym searches for the pair (k, tk) that produces the purest subsets (weighted by their size). The cost function that the algorithm tries to minimize is as follows: $$J(k,t_k) = \frac{m_{left}}{m}G_{left} + \frac{m_{right}}{m}G_{right}$$

  • $G_{left/right}$ measures the impurity of the left/right subset,
  • $m_{left/right}$ is the number of instances in the left/right subset.

Important Notes:

Scikit-Learn uses the CART algorithm, which produces only binary trees: nonleaf nodes always have two children. However, other algorithms such as ID3 can produce Decision Trees with nodes that have more than two children.

$$\begin{array}{c|c} Outlook & Yes & No & Instances \\ \hline Sunny & 2 & 3 & 5 \\ \hline Overcast & 2 & 0 & 2 \\ \hline Rainy & 3 & 1 & 4 \\ \end{array}$$

Temperature

$$\begin{array}{c|c} Temperature & Yes & No & Instances \\ \hline Hot & 1 & 2 & 3 \\ \hline Mild & 3 & 1 & 4 \\ \hline Cold & 3 & 1 & 4 \\ \end{array}$$

For All our Variables We now Want to calculate their Gini Index To Determine The Root Node

Below is just for the Condition Variable but you would do this for each variables

Sunny vs Other

$$\begin{array}{c|c} & Yes & No & Instances \\ \hline Sunny & 2 & 3 & 5 \\ \hline Other & 5 & 1 & 6 \end{array}$$

Gini Impurity

$$ Sunny = 1 - (\frac{2}{2+3})^{2} - (\frac{3}{2+3})^{2}$$

$$ GR = 0.48 $$

$$ Other = 1 - (\frac{5}{5+1})^{2} - (\frac{1}{5+1})^{2}$$

$$ GL = 0.278$$

Weighted Average

$$J(k,t_k) = \frac{m_{left}}{m}G_{left} + \frac{m_{right}}{m}G_{right}$$


$$\frac{5}{5+6}0.48 + \frac{6}{5+6}0.278$$

$$= 0.369 $$

Overcast vs Other

$$\begin{array}{c|c} & Yes & No & Instances \\ \hline Overcast & 2 & 0 & 2 \\ \hline Other & 5 & 4 & 9 \end{array}$$

Gini Impurity

$$ Overcast = 1 - (\frac{2}{2+0})^{2} - (\frac{0}{2+0})^{2}$$

$$ GR = 0 $$

$$ Other = 1 - (\frac{5}{5+4})^{2} - (\frac{4}{5+4})^{2}$$

$$ GL = 0.49$$

Weighted Average

$$J(k,t_k) = \frac{m_{left}}{m}G_{left} + \frac{m_{right}}{m}G_{right}$$


$$\frac{2}{2+9}0 + \frac{9}{2+9}0.49$$

$$= 0.4 $$

Rainy vs Other

$$\begin{array}{c|c} & Yes & No & Instances \\ \hline Rainy & 3 & 1 & 4 \\ \hline Other & 4 & 3 & 7 \end{array}$$

Gini Impurity

$$ Rainy = 1 - (\frac{3}{1+3})^{2} - (\frac{1}{1+3})^{2}$$

$$ GR = 0.375 $$

$$ Other = 1 - (\frac{4}{4+3})^{2} - (\frac{3}{4+3})^{2}$$

$$ GL = 0.49$$

Weighted Average

$$J(k,t_k) = \frac{m_{left}}{m}G_{left} + \frac{m_{right}}{m}G_{right}$$


$$\frac{4}{4+7}0.375 + \frac{7}{4+7}0.49$$

$$= 0.448 $$

Decision For our Root Node Is Outlook Sunny

In terms of Weighted Gini Index Values Outlook Sunny results in the Purest nodes

Interpreation

  1. We can see from our calculation that Outlook_Sunny contained the lowest impurity so it became our root node.

    • Now we need to know how well Temperature, Humidity, and Wind separate the Decision in our internal node

    • Once it has successfully split the training set in two, it splits the subsets using the same logic, then the sub-subsets and so on, recursively.

  1. Just like before we calculate the gini impurity on these nodes using Temperature, Humidity, and Wind
  • The identifier with the lowest gini impurity will be used to separate these nodes
  1. Notably, if the node iteself has the lowest gini score then there is no point in separating that node any more

  • This becomes our leaf node

  • It stops recursing once it reaches the maximum depth

Continuous Data

In classification tasks some of our explanatory variables may be in the form of continuous variables. Therefore, we have three steps to follow to caluclate the gini index:

  1. Sort Observations by Continuous data.
  1. Calcuate the average value of adjacent Observations.
  1. Calculate the Gini Impurity For each Adjacent value

Patient Data

$$\begin{array}{c|c} \text{Weight} & \text{Heart Disease} \\ \hline 82 & 1 \\ \hline 105 & 0 \\ \hline 72 & 0 \\ \hline 85 & 0 \\ \hline 80 & 0 \\ \hline 90 & 1 \\ \hline 88 & 1 \\ \hline 95 & 1 \\ \hline 77 & 1 \\ \hline 86 & 1 \end{array}$$

Step 1: Sort Patients by weight¶

$$\begin{array}{c|c} \text{Weight} & \text{Heart Disease} \\ \hline 72 & 0 \\ \hline 77 & 1 \\ \hline 80 & 0 \\ \hline 82 & 1 \\ \hline 85 & 0 \\ \hline 86 & 1 \\ \hline 88 & 1 \\ \hline 90 & 1 \\ \hline 95 & 1 \\ \hline 105 & 1 \end{array}$$

Step 2: Calculate the average weight for adjacent patients (First three for illustration puposes)¶

$$\begin{array}{c|c} \text{Weight} & \text{Heart Disease} & \text{Average} \\ \hline 72 & 0 & \\ \hline 77 & 1 & 74.5\\ \hline 80 & 0 & 78.5\\ \hline 82 & 1 & 81\\ \hline 85 & 0 & 83.5\\ \hline 86 & 1 & 85.5\\ \hline 88 & 1 & 87\\ \hline 90 & 1 & 89\\ \hline 95 & 1 & 92.5\\ \hline 105 & 1 & 100 \end{array}$$

Step 3: Calculate the Gini Impurity For each Adjacent value¶

74.5

$$\begin{array}{c|c} Weight & Yes & No & Instances \\ \hline 74.5 \leq & 0 & 1 & 1\\ \hline 74.5 \geq & 7 & 2 & 9 \end{array}$$

Gini Impurity

$$ GL = 1 - (\frac{0}{1+0})^{2} - (\frac{1}{1+0})^{2}$$

$$= 0 $$

$$ GR = 1 - (\frac{7}{7+2})^{2} - (\frac{2}{7+2})^{2}$$

$$= 0.345 $$

Weighted Average

$$J(k,t_k) = \frac{m_{left}}{m}G_{left} + \frac{m_{right}}{m}G_{right}$$

$$\text{Weighted Average} = \frac{1}{1+9}0 + \frac{9}{1+9}0.345 $$

$$= 0.31 $$

Next Pair¶

78.5

$$\begin{array}{c|c} Weight & Yes & No & Instances \\ \hline 78.5 \leq & 1 & 1 & 2\\ \hline 78.5 \geq & 6 & 2 & 8 \end{array}$$

Gini Impurity

$$ GL = 1 - (\frac{1}{1+1})^{2} - (\frac{1}{1+1})^{2}$$

$$= 0.5 $$

$$ GR = 1 - (\frac{6}{6+2})^{2} - (\frac{2}{6+2})^{2}$$

$$= 0.375 $$

Weighted Average

$$J(k,t_k) = \frac{m_{left}}{m}G_{left} + \frac{m_{right}}{m}G_{right}$$

$$\text{Weighted Average} = \frac{2}{8+2}0.5 + \frac{8}{8+2}0.375 $$

$$= 0.4 $$

Next Pair¶

81

$$\begin{array}{c|c} Weight & Yes & No & Instances \\ \hline 81 \leq & 1 & 2 & 3\\ \hline 81 \geq & 6 & 1 & 7 \end{array}$$

Gini Impurity

$$ GL = 1 - (\frac{1}{2+1})^{2} - (\frac{2}{2+1})^{2}$$

$$= 0.44 $$

$$ GR = 1 - (\frac{6}{6+1})^{2} - (\frac{1}{6+1})^{2}$$

$$= 0.244 $$

Weighted Average

$$J(k,t_k) = \frac{m_{left}}{m}G_{left} + \frac{m_{right}}{m}G_{right}$$

$$\text{Weighted Average} = \frac{3}{7+3}0.44 + \frac{7}{7+3}0.244 $$

$$= 0.302 $$

Interpreation

The lowest impurity occurs when we separate using weight is $\leq 85.5$

Estimating Class Probabilities

  • A Decision Tree can return the estimated probability that an instance belongs to a certain class.
  • Our algorithym traverses the tree to find a leaf node for this $i^{th}$ instance and then it return the ratio.

Regularization

Decision Trees make very few assumptions about the training data and as such this model is often called a nonparametric model, not because it does not have any parameters prior to training so the model structure is free to stick closely to the data. The DecisionTreeClassifier class has a few parameters that similarly restrict the shape of the Decision Tree. Below we will show how a model overfits when our max depth is set from 2 to 4.

Regression Tree

The main difference between classification trees and regression trees is that instead of predicting a class in each node, it predicts a value. The CART algorithm works similar to our classification but instead splitting the training set in a way that minimizes impurity, we are now trying to split the training set in a way that minimizes the mean Squared Error or the sum of our residuals.

The CART Training Algorithm

Scikit-Learn uses the Classification And Regression Tree (CART) algorithm to train Decision Trees¶

This algorithym searches for the pair (k, tk) that produces the purest subsets (weighted by their size). The cost function that the algorithm tries to minimize is as follows:

$$J(k,t_k) = \frac{m_{left}}{m}MSE_{left} + \frac{m_{right}}{m}MSE_{right}$$

where: $$MSE_{node} = \sum_{i \in node} (\hat{y}_{node} - y^{(i)})^2$$

$$\hat{y}_{node} = \frac{1}{m_{node}}\sum_{i \in node} (y^{(i)})$$

Worked Example

Data Scientist Salary DataSet

$$\begin{array}{c|c} Experience & Degree & Salary\\ \hline 2 & Bachelor & 58 \\ \hline 3 & Masters & 72 \\ \hline 3 & Masters & 76 \\ \hline 5 & Bachelor & 80\\ \hline 7 & PHD & 100 \\ \hline 7 & Masters & 87\\ \hline 4 & PHD & 110\\ \hline 1 & Bachelor & 52 \end{array}$$

Weighted Average

$$\text{Weighted Average} = \frac{3}{5+3}435+ \frac{5}{5+3}205 $$

$$= 291 $$

    fig = plot_decision_regions(X=X, y=y, clf=clfs, legend=2)
    plt.title(lab)

plt.savefig('MaxDepthRegularization.png')
